{
  "In nuclear equations, both mass number and atomic number must be:": "",
  "Halved on both sides of the equation": "",
  "Destroyed during the nuclear process": "",
  "Created from energy during the reaction": "",
  "Conserved (balanced) on both sides": "",
  "In nuclear equations, the total mass number and total atomic number must be the same on both sides of the equation. This is the law of conservation of mass number and atomic number, which is used to balance nuclear equations and identify unknown products.": "",
  "Transmutation is the conversion of:": "",
  "Energy to mass in a nuclear event": "",
  "One element into another element": "",
  "An acid into a base by neutralization": "",
  "A solid into a liquid by heating it": "",
  "Transmutation is the conversion of one element into another by changing the number of protons in the nucleus. This can happen naturally through radioactive decay or artificially by bombarding nuclei with particles in a particle accelerator.": "",
  "Artificial transmutation can be achieved by:": "",
  "Heating a substance to very high temperatures": "",
  "Applying extremely high pressures to a sample": "",
  "Bombarding nuclei with particles in an accelerator": "",
  "Dissolving the substance in water or acid": "",
  "Artificial transmutation is achieved by bombarding atomic nuclei with high-energy particles (such as protons, neutrons, or alpha particles) using a particle accelerator. This was first accomplished by Ernest Rutherford in 1919 when he converted nitrogen into oxygen.": "",
  "When uranium-238 undergoes alpha decay, it becomes:": "",
  "Thorium-234, with 2 fewer protons and 4 fewer nucleons": "",
  "Radium-226, with 4 fewer protons and 12 fewer nucleons": "",
  "Uranium-234, with the same protons and 4 fewer nucleons": "",
  "Plutonium-242, with 2 more protons and 4 more nucleons": "",
  "In alpha decay, the nucleus loses 2 protons and 2 neutrons (an alpha particle). Uranium-238 (Z=92, A=238) becomes thorium-234 (Z=90, A=234). The atomic number drops by 2 and the mass number drops by 4.": "",
  "A positron is the antiparticle of:": "",
  "A neutron found in the nucleus": "",
  "An electron with the same mass but opposite charge": "",
  "A proton found in the nucleus": "",
  "An alpha particle emitted during decay": "",
  "A positron has the same mass as an electron but carries a positive charge instead of a negative one. In positron emission, a proton in the nucleus converts to a neutron and a positron is emitted, decreasing the atomic number by 1.": "",
  "Positron emission decreases the atomic number by:": "",
  "0, the atomic number stays the same": "",
  "2, since two protons are converted": "",
  "1 (a proton converts to a neutron)": "",
  "4, since an alpha particle is also emitted": "",
  "In positron emission, a proton in the nucleus converts to a neutron and emits a positron. This decreases the atomic number by 1 because the nucleus has one fewer proton. The mass number stays the same because the total number of nucleons is unchanged.": "",
  "In electron capture:": "",
  "A neutron escapes from the nucleus": "",
  "A proton is emitted from the nucleus": "",
  "An electron is emitted from the nucleus": "",
  "An inner electron is absorbed by the nucleus": "",
  "In electron capture, the nucleus pulls in (captures) an inner-shell electron. This electron combines with a proton to form a neutron. The atomic number decreases by 1, but the mass number stays the same. The result is similar to positron emission.": "",
  "What happens to the atomic number and mass number during gamma emission?": "",
  "The atomic number increases by 1 and the mass number stays the same": "",
  "Both the atomic number and mass number remain unchanged": "",
  "The atomic number decreases by 2 and the mass number decreases by 4": "",
  "The mass number decreases by 1 and the atomic number stays the same": "",
  "Gamma emission releases energy as a high-energy photon. Since the photon has no mass and no charge, the atomic number and mass number of the nucleus both remain unchanged. The nucleus simply moves from an excited state to a lower energy state.": "",
  "The first artificial transmutation was performed by Ernest Rutherford, who converted nitrogen into:": "",
  "Carbon, by removing a proton": "",
  "Helium, by splitting the nucleus": "",
  "Oxygen, by bombarding it with alpha particles": "",
  "Fluorine, by adding two protons": "",
  "In 1919, Rutherford bombarded nitrogen-14 with alpha particles and produced oxygen-17 and a proton. This was the first time a human-made nuclear reaction converted one element into another, demonstrating that artificial transmutation was possible.": "",
  "Electron capture has the same effect on the atomic number as:": "",
  "Alpha decay, which decreases it by 2": "",
  "Beta-minus decay, which increases it by 1": "",
  "Gamma emission, which does not change it": "",
  "Positron emission, which decreases it by 1": "",
  "Both electron capture and positron emission decrease the atomic number by 1. In electron capture, an electron combines with a proton to form a neutron. In positron emission, a proton converts to a neutron and emits a positron. The net result for the nucleus is the same.": "",
  "What is a nuclear equation?": "",
  "A symbolic representation of a nuclear reaction showing reactant and product nuclei with their atomic and mass numbers": "",
  "A mathematical formula that calculates the energy released during chemical combustion reactions": "",
  "A diagram showing the arrangement of electrons in the energy levels around an atom": "",
  "A balanced chemical equation showing the rearrangement of atoms in a chemical reaction": "",
  "A nuclear equation is a symbolic representation of a nuclear reaction. It shows the parent nucleus, emitted particles, and daughter nucleus, each with their mass number (superscript) and atomic number (subscript). Both mass number and atomic number must be balanced on each side.": "",
  "What is transmutation?": "",
  "The change of a substance from one physical state to another, such as solid to liquid": "",
  "The conversion of one element into a different element by changing the number of protons in the nucleus": "",
  "The rearrangement of atoms in a molecule during a standard chemical reaction process": "",
  "The transfer of electrons from one atom to another during an ionic bonding process": "",
  "Transmutation is the conversion of one element into another by changing the number of protons in the nucleus. This can occur naturally through radioactive decay or artificially through particle bombardment. Since the number of protons defines the element, any change in proton count creates a new element.": "",
  "Define 'positron emission' in nuclear chemistry.": "",
  "The emission of a high-energy electron from the nucleus when a neutron converts to a proton": "",
  "The absorption of an inner-shell electron by the nucleus to convert a proton into a neutron": "",
  "A nuclear decay where a proton converts to a neutron and a positron is emitted, decreasing the atomic number by 1": "",
  "The release of a helium-4 nucleus from a heavy atom, reducing atomic number by 2 and mass number by 4": "",
  "Positron emission is a type of radioactive decay in which a proton in the nucleus converts to a neutron and emits a positron (a particle with the same mass as an electron but a positive charge). The atomic number decreases by 1, and the mass number stays the same.": "",
  "What is 'electron capture' in nuclear chemistry?": "",
  "The emission of a beta particle when a neutron becomes a proton inside the nucleus": "",
  "The removal of a valence electron by applying an external electric field to the atom": "",
  "The release of gamma radiation as the nucleus drops from an excited energy state to ground": "",
  "A process where the nucleus absorbs an inner-shell electron, converting a proton to a neutron": "",
  "Electron capture occurs when the nucleus absorbs an inner-shell (usually K-shell) electron. This electron combines with a proton to form a neutron. The atomic number decreases by 1, and the mass number remains the same. It produces the same result as positron emission.": "",
  "What does it mean to 'balance' a nuclear equation?": "",
  "Ensuring that the sum of mass numbers and the sum of atomic numbers are equal on both sides": "",
  "Making sure that both sides of the equation have the same number of individual atoms": "",
  "Ensuring that the energy on the reactant side equals the energy on the product side": "",
  "Confirming that the same elements appear on both sides of the nuclear equation arrow": "",
  "Balancing a nuclear equation means ensuring the total mass numbers (superscripts) and total atomic numbers (subscripts) are equal on both sides of the arrow. This reflects the conservation of nucleons and charge in nuclear reactions.": "",
  "What is a 'particle accelerator' used for in nuclear chemistry?": "",
  "Slowing down radioactive decay to make isotopes last longer for research purposes": "",
  "Speeding up charged particles to high energies so they can bombard and transform nuclei": "",
  "Cooling nuclear fuel rods to prevent meltdowns in commercial nuclear power plants": "",
  "Measuring the half-life of radioactive isotopes by counting decay events over time": "",
  "A particle accelerator uses electric and magnetic fields to speed up charged particles (protons, alpha particles, etc.) to very high energies. These fast-moving particles are then aimed at target nuclei to cause artificial transmutation or to study nuclear structure.": "",
  "What is 'natural transmutation'?": "",
  "The conversion of one element to another caused by bombarding it with particles in a lab": "",
  "The change from one physical state to another when temperature or pressure changes": "",
  "The spontaneous change of one element into another through radioactive decay without human intervention": "",
  "The process by which chemical bonds break and reform during a standard chemical reaction": "",
  "Natural transmutation occurs spontaneously when an unstable nucleus undergoes radioactive decay, changing into a different element. For example, uranium-238 naturally decays to thorium-234 through alpha decay. No human intervention or external bombardment is needed.": "",
  "What is the difference between a nuclear reaction and a chemical reaction?": "",
  "Chemical reactions involve changes in the nucleus while nuclear reactions involve only electrons": "",
  "Nuclear reactions only occur at extremely cold temperatures while chemical reactions need heat": "",
  "Both types of reactions are identical in every way and produce the same amount of energy": "",
  "Nuclear reactions change the nucleus and can create new elements; chemical reactions only rearrange electrons": "",
  "Nuclear reactions involve changes to the protons and neutrons in the nucleus, which can transform one element into another and release enormous energy. Chemical reactions only involve the rearrangement of electrons in bonds and do not change the identity of elements.": "",
  "Define the term 'artificial transmutation.'": "",
  "The human-caused conversion of one element into another by bombarding nuclei with high-energy particles": "",
  "The spontaneous decay of a radioactive nucleus into a lighter element without any external cause": "",
  "The synthesis of new chemical compounds by mixing two or more elements in a laboratory flask": "",
  "The conversion of energy into matter that occurs inside stars during nuclear fusion events": "",
  "Artificial transmutation is the deliberate conversion of one element into another by bombarding atomic nuclei with high-energy particles in a particle accelerator. This technique has been used to create synthetic elements like technetium and all elements beyond uranium.": "",
  "What does the subscript number represent in nuclear notation?": "",
  "The total number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus (mass number)": "",
  "The atomic number, which is the number of protons in the nucleus": "",
  "The number of electrons in the outermost energy level of the atom": "",
  "The energy level of the most tightly bound electron in the atom": "",
  "In nuclear notation, the subscript (bottom number) represents the atomic number (Z), which is the number of protons. The superscript (top number) represents the mass number (A), which is the total number of protons and neutrons. Both must balance in a nuclear equation.": "",
  "A student is balancing a nuclear equation for the alpha decay of radium-226 (Ra, Z=88). What should the daughter nucleus be?": "",
  "Radon-222 (Rn, Z=86), because alpha decay decreases atomic number by 2 and mass number by 4": "",
  "Actinium-226 (Ac, Z=89), because alpha decay increases the atomic number by 1": "",
  "Francium-222 (Fr, Z=87), because alpha decay decreases atomic number by 1 and mass by 4": "",
  "Polonium-222 (Po, Z=84), because alpha decay decreases the atomic number by 4": "",
  "In alpha decay, the atomic number decreases by 2 and the mass number decreases by 4. Radium-226 (Z=88, A=226) emits an alpha particle and becomes radon-222 (Z=86, A=222). This is how the equation is balanced: 88 - 2 = 86 and 226 - 4 = 222.": "",
  "A scientist uses a particle accelerator to bombard aluminum-27 (Z=13) with alpha particles and produces phosphorus-30 (Z=15) plus another particle. What is the other particle?": "",
  "A proton, because the atomic numbers do not balance otherwise": "",
  "An alpha particle, because two alpha particles are always produced": "",
  "An electron, because beta decay must accompany the transmutation": "",
  "A neutron, because balancing the mass and atomic numbers requires it": "",
  "Balancing: Al-27 (Z=13, A=27) + He-4 (Z=2, A=4) produces P-30 (Z=15, A=30) + unknown. Mass numbers: 27+4 = 31, and 30+? = 31, so ? = 1. Atomic numbers: 13+2 = 15, and 15+? = 15, so ? = 0. A particle with A=1 and Z=0 is a neutron.": "",
  "A lab technician observes that after a nuclear reaction, the element on the periodic table has shifted one position to the right. Which type of decay most likely occurred?": "",
  "Alpha decay, which decreases the atomic number by 2": "",
  "Beta-minus decay, which increases the atomic number by 1": "",
  "Gamma emission, which does not change the atomic number": "",
  "Positron emission, which decreases the atomic number by 1": "",
  "Moving one position to the right on the periodic table means the atomic number increased by 1. Beta-minus decay is the process that increases the atomic number by 1, as a neutron converts to a proton. Alpha decay moves 2 positions to the left, positron emission moves 1 to the left, and gamma emission causes no change.": "",
  "A researcher needs to create technetium-99m for medical imaging. Since technetium does not occur naturally, how is it produced?": "",
  "By extracting it from uranium ore through chemical separation techniques": "",
  "By fusing two lighter elements together in a high-temperature fusion reactor": "",
  "By exposing stable molybdenum to radiation, causing it to undergo nuclear transmutation": "",
  "By cooling plutonium until it naturally decays into technetium over several days": "",
  "Technetium-99m is produced by artificial transmutation. Molybdenum-98 is bombarded with neutrons in a nuclear reactor to produce molybdenum-99, which then decays by beta emission into technetium-99m. This is one of the most important isotopes in nuclear medicine.": "",
  "A student is asked to identify the missing particle in this nuclear equation: N-14 (Z=7) + He-4 (Z=2) -> O-17 (Z=8) + ?. What is the missing particle?": "",
  "A neutron (mass number 1, atomic number 0)": "",
  "An electron (mass number 0, atomic number -1)": "",
  "A gamma ray (mass number 0, atomic number 0)": "",
  "A proton (mass number 1, atomic number 1)": "",
  "Balancing the equation: Mass numbers: 14 + 4 = 17 + ?, so ? = 1. Atomic numbers: 7 + 2 = 8 + ?, so ? = 1. A particle with mass number 1 and atomic number 1 is a proton. This is Rutherford's famous transmutation experiment.": "",
  "A chemistry teacher explains that all elements heavier than uranium on the periodic table are synthetic. How were these transuranium elements created?": "",
  "They were discovered in meteorites that fell to Earth from outer space": "",
  "They were created by artificial transmutation using particle accelerators or nuclear reactors": "",
  "They formed naturally in deep ocean vents under extreme heat and pressure": "",
  "They were extracted from volcanic rock using advanced chemical separation methods": "",
  "Transuranium elements (those with atomic numbers greater than 92) are all synthetic. They were created through artificial transmutation by bombarding heavy nuclei with particles in accelerators or reactors. Examples include neptunium (93), plutonium (94), and oganesson (118).": "",
  "In a nuclear chemistry lab, a student writes the equation for the beta-minus decay of carbon-14 (Z=6). Which product nucleus should appear in the equation?": "",
  "Boron-14 (Z=5), because beta decay decreases the atomic number by 1": "",
  "Carbon-13 (Z=6), because beta decay decreases the mass number by 1": "",
  "Nitrogen-14 (Z=7), because beta-minus decay increases the atomic number by 1": "",
  "Oxygen-14 (Z=8), because beta-minus decay increases the atomic number by 2": "",
  "In beta-minus decay, a neutron converts to a proton and an electron is emitted. Carbon-14 (Z=6) gains one proton, becoming nitrogen-14 (Z=7). The mass number stays at 14 because the total number of nucleons is unchanged.": "",
  "A student reads about medieval alchemists who tried to turn lead into gold using chemical methods. Why was their approach doomed to fail?": "",
  "Lead and gold have the same number of protons so no transformation is needed": "",
  "Chemical reactions cannot change the number of protons in a nucleus; only nuclear reactions can transform elements": "",
  "Gold is a compound, not an element, so it cannot be made from lead atoms": "",
  "The alchemists did not have access to strong enough acids to dissolve the lead": "",
  "Converting lead to gold requires changing the number of protons (lead has 82, gold has 79). Chemical reactions only rearrange electrons and bonds — they cannot alter the nucleus. Only nuclear reactions (transmutation) can change one element into another.": "",
  "A nuclear engineer is designing a reactor and needs to understand what happens when U-235 (Z=92) absorbs a neutron and undergoes fission into Ba-141 (Z=56) and Kr-92 (Z=36). How many neutrons are released?": "",
  "1 neutron is released in this fission event": "",
  "2 neutrons are released in this fission event": "",
  "3 neutrons are released in this fission event": "",
  "4 neutrons are released in this fission event": "",
  "Balancing mass numbers: U-235 + 1 neutron = 236 total. Products: Ba-141 + Kr-92 = 233. So 236 - 233 = 3 neutrons are released. Balancing atomic numbers: 92 + 0 = 56 + 36 + 0 = 92, confirmed. These 3 neutrons can go on to cause more fission events in a chain reaction.": "",
  "A student is given an unknown nuclear equation where phosphorus-32 (Z=15) decays into sulfur-32 (Z=16) plus a particle. The student must identify the decay type and the emitted particle. What are they?": "",
  "Alpha decay, emitting a helium-4 nucleus from the phosphorus atom": "",
  "Gamma emission, releasing a high-energy photon without changing the element": "",
  "Positron emission, where a proton converts to a neutron in the nucleus": "",
  "Beta-minus decay, emitting an electron as a neutron converts to a proton": "",
  "The atomic number increased from 15 to 16 (an increase of 1) while the mass number stayed at 32. This is characteristic of beta-minus decay, where a neutron converts to a proton and emits an electron. The emitted particle is a beta particle (high-energy electron).": ""
}